---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Types of Pedestrian Accident Claims | pedestrianaccidentcalc.com';
const description = 'Overview of pedestrian accident claim types: crosswalk accidents, hit and run, parking lot accidents, and DUI strikes.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Types of Pedestrian Accident Claims</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Crosswalk accidents</h2><p>Driver fails to yield to a pedestrian in a marked or unmarked crosswalk. Pedestrian has the right of way in most states when in a crosswalk with a green or walk signal. Strongest liability position for the pedestrian.</p>
  <h2>Hit and run</h2><p>Driver flees the scene after striking a pedestrian. Prosecuted criminally; civil recovery via UM coverage. Report immediately and document all witnesses. Some states have funds for uncompensated crime victims that may apply.</p>
  <h2>DUI / impaired driver</h2><p>Driver under the influence strikes a pedestrian. Clear negligence; punitive damages available in most states. Enhanced criminal penalties. Dram shop liability may attach if the driver was served at a bar before the accident.</p>
  <h2>Parking lot and driveway accidents</h2><p>Lower speed but still cause serious injury. Property owner liability may apply if the lot design was dangerous. Driver is still liable for failing to yield to pedestrians in parking areas.</p>
  <h2>Construction zone accidents</h2><p>Pedestrians struck near construction sites. General contractor, subcontractor, and property owner may all have liability. These cases often involve multiple defendants with available insurance coverage.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-pedestrian-accident-claims-work">how pedestrian accident claims work</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
